]]\n[[Category:1986 births]]\n[[Category:Elegies (group) members]]\n[[Category:Happy 7 members]]\n[[Category:Japanese idols]]\n[[Category:Former Hello! Project members]]\n[[Category:Japanese female models]]\n[[Category:Japanese actresses]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Minimoni members]]\n[[Category:Morning Musume members]]\n[[Category:Actors from Fukui Prefecture]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Fukui Prefecture]]\n", "name_user": "WalterRalts123456", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ai_Takahashi"}
{"title_page": "Battle of Sarantaporo", "text_new": "{{good article}}\n{{Infobox Military Conflict\n|conflict=Battle of Sarantaporo\n|partof=the [[First Balkan War]]   \n|image=Sarantaporo.png\n|image_size=250px\n|caption=Map of the battle\n|date=9 \u2013 10 October 1912 (O.S.)    \n|place=[[Sarantaporo]], [[Manastir Vilayet]], [[Ottoman Empire]] (present-day [[Greece]])  \n|result= Greek victory \n* Greek army captures [[Servia, Greece|Servia]] and [[Kozani]]\n|map_type    = Greece\n| map_label   =Sarantaporo\n|map_relief  = yes\n|alt         = A relief map of modern day Greece, with the location of the battle marked.\n|map_caption ={{center|Location of the battle in present day Greece}}\n|coordinates={{coord|40.0400|N|22.0300|E|display=title}}\n|combatant1={{flagicon|Greece|royal}} [[Kingdom of Greece|Greece]]  \n|combatant2={{flag|Ottoman Empire}}   \n|commander1=Crown Prince [[Constantine I of Greece|Constantine]]\n|commander2=General [[Hasan Tahsin Pasha]]\n|units1=[[Order of battle of the Hellenic Army in the First Balkan War#Army of Thessaly|Army of Thessaly]]\n*[[1st Infantry Division (Greece)|1st Infantry Division]]\n*[[2nd Infantry Division (Greece)|2nd Infantry Division]]\n*[[3rd Infantry Division (Greece)|3rd Infantry Division]]\n*[[4th Infantry Division (Greece)|4th Infantry Division]]   \n*[[5th Infantry Division (Greece)|5th Infantry Division]]\n|units2=[[VIII Corps (Ottoman Empire)|VIII Provisional Corps]]\n*[[22nd Infantry Division (Ottoman Empire)|22nd Infantry Division]]\n*Nasli\u00e7 Division\n|strength1=''5 divisions''\n|strength2=''2 divisions''\n|casualties1=182 killed<br>1,000 wounded {{sfn|Christopoulos|Bastias|1977|p=292}}\n|casualties2=500 killed<br />1,000 wounded<br />22-25 field artillery pieces {{sfn|Erickson|2003|pp=218\u2013219}}\n}}   \n{{Campaignbox First Balkan War}}\n\nThe '''Battle of Sarantaporo''', also variously transliterated as '''Sarantaporon''' or '''Sarandaporon''' ({{lang-el|\u039c\u03ac\u03c7\u03b7 \u03c4\u03bf\u03c5 \u03a3\u03b1\u03c1\u03b1\u03bd\u03c4\u03b1\u03c0\u03cc\u03c1\u03bf\u03c5}}), took place on October 9 \u2013 10 (O.S.), 1912. It was the first major battle fought between [[Kingdom of Greece|Greek]] and [[Ottoman Empire|Ottoman]] forces during the [[First Balkan War]], and revolved around the Sarandaporo pass, which connected [[Thessaly]] with central [[Macedonia (region)|Macedonia]].\n\nDespite being perceived as impregnable by its defenders, the main body of the Greek forces managed to advance deep inside the pass, while auxiliary units broke through the Ottoman flanks. The Ottomans abandoned their defensive line during the night, fearing encirclement. The Greek victory at Sarandaporo opened the way for the capture of [[Servia, Greece|Servia]] and [[Kozani]].\n\n==Background==\nThe disastrous Greek defeat in the [[Greco-Turkish War (1897)|Greco-Turkish War]] of 1897 exposed major flaws in the [[Greek Army]]'s organization, training and logistics. Upon his appointment in December 1905, [[Georgios Theotokis]] became the first post-war Greek prime minister to focus his attention on strengthening the army. He established the National Defense Fund which financed the purchase of large quantities of ammunition. In addition a new [[table of organization]] was introduced for the country's [[Greek Navy|navy]] and army, the latter being augmented by numerous artillery batteries. Theotokis' resignation in January 1909 and the perceived neglect of the armed forces by his successor resulted in the [[Goudi coup]] seven months later. Rather than taking power for themselves, the putschists invited Cretan politician [[Eleftherios Venizelos]] to rule the country.{{sfn|Kargakos|2012|pp=19\u201321}} Venizelos followed in Theotokis' footsteps by continuing to re-arm and re-train the military, enacted extensive fortification and infrastructure works, purchased new weapons, and recalled the [[Military reserve force|reserve classes]] for training. The climax of this effort was the invitation in 1911 of a [[British naval mission to Greece (1911\u20131915)|British naval mission]] and a [[French military mission to Greece (1911\u20131914)|French military mission]].{{sfn|Katsikostas|2014|pp=5\u20136}} \n\nAfter being informed of a Serbo-Bulgarian alliance, Venizelos ordered his ambassador in [[Sofia]] to prepare a Greco-Bulgarian defense agreement by 14 April 1912. Fearing that should Greece fail to participate in a future war against the [[Ottoman Empire|Ottomans]], it would be unable to capture the Greek majority areas of [[Macedonia (region)|Macedonia]]. The treaty was signed on 15 July 1912, with the two countries agreeing to assist each other in case of a defensive war and to safeguard the rights of Christian populations in Ottoman held Macedonia, thus joining the loose [[Balkan League]] alliance with [[Serbia]], [[Montenegro]] and [[Bulgaria]]. Fearing a new war in the Balkans, the Ottomans mobilized their armed forces on 14 September and began transferring units to [[Thrace]]; the Balkan League responded in kind.{{sfn|Kargakos|2012|pp=26\u201329}} On 30 September, the League presented the Ottomans with a list of demands regarding the rights of its Christian population. The Ottoman Empire rebuffed the demands, recalled its ambassadors in Sofia, Belgrade and Athens and expelled the League's negotiators on 4 October. The League's negotiators declared [[First Balkan War|war]] against the Ottomans, while Montenegro had already began military operations on 25 September.{{sfn|Kargakos|2012|pp=35\u201338}}\n\n==Prelude==\nGreece dispatched the [[Army of Epirus]] and the [[Army of Thessaly]] to its frontiers in [[Epirus]] and [[Thessaly]] respectively. The latter numbered 100,000 men, and was divided into seven divisions: namely the [[1st Infantry Division (Greece)|1st Infantry Division]], the [[2nd Infantry Division (Greece)|2nd Infantry Division]], the [[3rd Infantry Division (Greece)|3rd Infantry Division]], the [[4th Infantry Division (Greece)|4th Infantry Division]], the [[5th Infantry Division (Greece)|5th Infantry Division]], the [[6th Infantry Division (Greece)|6th Infantry Division]] and the [[7th Mechanized Infantry Brigade (Greece)|7th Infantry Division]], as well as a cavalry brigade and four independent [[Evzones]] battalions. The Army of Thessaly was commanded by Crown Prince [[Constantine I of Greece|Constantine]].{{sfn|Christopoulos|Bastias|1977|pp=289\u2013290}} Facing the Greeks in Thessaly was the Ottoman [[VIII Corps (Ottoman Empire)|VIII Corps]] under General [[Hasan Tahsin Pasha]] which included three divisions: the regular (''nizamiye'') [[22nd Infantry Division (Ottoman Empire)|22nd Division]] and the reserve (''redif'') Nasli\u00e7 and Ayd\u0131n Divisions{{sfn|Erickson|2003|p=170}} which, combined with the Ottoman garrisons in western Macedonia, totaled 35,000-40,000 men.{{sfn|Christopoulos|Bastias|1977|p=290}}\n\nThe Army of Thessaly crossed into Ottoman territory in the early morning hours of 5 October, finding most border posts to be abandoned, with the garrisons at Melouna Pass, Profitis Ilias and Tsouka resisting for several hours before retreating. The first major clashes took place the following day when the 1st and 2nd Greek Divisions attacked hastily organized defenses north of [[Elassona]]. Elassona was defended by three infantry battalions, two artillery batteries and half a squadron of cavalry.{{sfn|Christopoulos|Bastias|1977|p=290}} The battle for Elassona lasted for three hours, with the Ottomans retreating to avoid encirclement, thus giving the troops manning the main defensive line at Sarandaporo additional time to reinforce their positions.{{sfn|Kargakos|2012|pp=44\u201345}} The Greeks went on to advance {{convert|20|km|miles}} into the Elassona plateau without encountering any resistance.{{sfn|Kargakos|2012|p=47}} Between 7 and 8 October, Greek troops regrouped in front of Sarandaporo and dispatched cavalry reconnaissance patrols towards the Ottoman positions, locating the headquarters of the Ottoman VIII Provisional Corps at Hania Viglas and those of a reserve division at Glikovo.{{sfn|Christopoulos|Bastias|1977|p=290}}\n\nSituated between the Vigla and Amorves mountains, Sarandaporo was a narrow mountain pass, the only one connecting Thessaly with central Macedonia; it spanned some {{convert|7-8|km|miles|sigfig=1}}. Having ceded Thessaly to Greece in the [[Convention of Constantinople (1881)]], the Ottomans began methodically reinforcing their positions around Sarandaporo in anticipation of a future war.{{sfn|Kargakos|2012|p=48}} The Ottomans had organized their defenses under the guidance of German military advisors, placing their artillery batteries and infantry in sheltered, camouflaged trenches on the ravine's steep slopes, allowing them to accurately fire along its entire length. Considered to be nearly impenetrable it was dubbed \"the graveyard of the Greek Army\" by  the Prussian Field Marshal [[Colmar Freiherr von der Goltz]].{{sfn|Dimitracopoulos|1992|p=42}}\n\n==Battle==\nAt 7 a.m. on 9 October, the Greek infantry began its assault on Sarandaporo. The 1st, 2nd and 3rd Divisions attacked the Ottoman main line frontally, their advance hampered by accurate Ottoman rifle and artillery fire and the ruggedness of the terrain. In the meantime, the 4th Division conducted a flanking maneuver from the west with the intention of occupying the Porta Pass, and striking the rear of the Ottoman positions.{{sfn|Christopoulos|Bastias|1977|p=291}} The 5th Division advanced further to the west towards the village of Zampourda which was situated on the other bank of the [[Haliacmon]], with the intention of protecting the left flank of the Greek forces emerging from the Sarandaporo pass. The cavalry brigade moved on the extreme west along the road towards [[Servia, Greece|Servia]], planning to block the bridge across the Haliacmon.{{sfn|Kargakos|2012|p=51}} Attacking from the east of the pass the Konstantinopoulos Evzone detachment overcame stiff resistance at Vlacholeivado and captured the village, but failing to advance further due to heavy fog.{{sfn|Apostolidis|1913|pp=207\u2013209}}{{sfn|Christopoulos|Bastias|1977|p=291}} At 2 p.m., the main bulk of the Greek artillery was brought to the main line, joining the engagement. Despite suffering heavy casualties, the three divisions had halted some {{convert|500-700|m|yards|sigfig=1}} from the Ottoman trenches intending to launch a final assault the following morning.{{sfn|Christopoulos|Bastias|1977|p=291}}\n\nThe 4th Division fought its way through the villages of Metaxas and Rachovo. Upon reaching the Porta Pass it engaged in a sanguinary clash with the defenders, securing its objective at 5 p.m.{{sfn|Kargakos|2012|p=53}} The 5th Division and the Gennadis Evzone detachment were confronted by four Ottoman reserve battalions at Lazarades which held their ground until sunset.{{sfn|Christopoulos|Bastias|1977|p=291}} The commander of the cavalry brigade ordered his unit to encamp at Loudani, refusing to advance further because of the resistance offered by the Ottomans at Lazarades. Fearing that they would be encircled by the Konstantinopoulos Evzone detachment, the Ottomans began to withdraw at 7 p.m., towards their second defensive line at Hani 739, under the cover of the night. Before retreating they fired a 20-minute artillery barrage on Greek positions along the entire frontline. Unaware of the Ottoman retreat the Greeks failed to use the opportunity and cut their access to the bridge across the Haliacmon. Upon reaching their second defensive line, the Ottomans became aware of the 4th Divisions' seizure of Porta Pass, panic spread in their ranks and many soldiers fled, abandoning their equipment.{{sfn|Apostolidis|1913|pp=203\u2013205}} On the morning of 10 October, the 4th Division charged down the northern slope of the Rahovo Mountain, surprising the Ottoman infantry and artillerymen who abandoned over twenty [[Krupp gun]]s and engaged in a disorganized retreat.{{sfn|Dimitracopoulos|1992|p=44}}{{sfn|Erickson|2003|pp=218\u2013219}} The Greek cavalry's indecision once again enabled the fleeing Ottomans to safely reach Servia and [[Kozani]].{{sfn|Kargakos|2012|pp=56\u201357}}\n\n==Aftermath==\nAt 4 p.m. on 10 October, the 4th Division entered Servia, witnessing 75 to 90 severed human heads lined up on either side of one of its streets.{{sfn|Dimitracopoulos|1992|p=44}}{{sfn|Christopoulos|Bastias|1977|p=292}} Following the declaration of war local authorities had detained all the Christian dignitaries from Servia and the surrounding villages with the intention of massacring them, a plan that was thwarted by Ottoman officer Omer Bey. However, upon realizing the imminent defeat of the Ottoman troops at Sarandaporo, the town's Muslim population massacred 117 local Christians.{{sfn|Kargakos|2012|pp=58\u201359}} By 11 October, the entirety of the Army of Thessaly had reached the banks of the Haliacmon, while the Greek cavalry entered Kozani unopposed,{{sfn|Christopoulos|Bastias|1977|p=292}} opening the way for the Greeks to advance towards the Greek majority city of [[Thessaloniki]] and assist the Serbs at [[Bitola|Monastir]].{{sfn|Dimitracopoulos|1992|p=46}} On 13 October, the Greek army transferred its general headquarters to Kozani; the following day King [[George I of Greece|George I]] arrived in the city, ordering the army to march towards Thessaloniki and [[Veroia]].{{sfn|Apostolidis|1913|pp=241\u2013243}} Greek casualties in the battle of Sarandaporo numbered 182 killed and over 1,000 wounded,{{sfn|Christopoulos|Bastias|1977|p=292}} while the Ottomans lost approximately 500 killed, 1,000 wounded, around 22 to 25 field artillery pieces captured and other significant material losses.{{sfn|Erickson|2003|pp=218\u2013219}}{{sfn|Dimitracopoulos|1992|p=44}}\n\nBy May 1913, the numerically inferior Ottomans had suffered a series of serious defeats to the League's armies on all fronts. The League had captured most of the Ottoman Empire's European territories and was rapidly approaching [[Constantinople]]. On 30 May, the two sides signed the [[Treaty of London (1913)|Treaty of London]] which solidified the League's territorial ambitions, granting its members all Ottoman lands west of [[Enos, Turkey|Enos]] on the [[Aegean Sea]] and north of [[K\u0131y\u0131k\u00f6y|Midia]] on the [[Black Sea]], as well as [[Crete]]. The fate of [[Albania]] and the Ottoman-held Aegean islands was to be determined by the [[International relations of the Great Powers (1814\u20131919)|Great Powers]].{{sfn|Christopoulos|Bastias|1977|pp=330\u2013332}}\n\n==Footnotes==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==References==\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite book |last=Apostolidis |first=Dimitrios |title=\u039f \u03bd\u03b9\u03ba\u03b7\u03c6\u03cc\u03c1\u03bf\u03c2 \u03b5\u03bb\u03bb\u03b7\u03bd\u03bf\u03c4\u03bf\u03c5\u03c1\u03ba\u03b9\u03ba\u03cc\u03c2 \u03c0\u03cc\u03bb\u03b5\u03bc\u03bf\u03c2 \u03c4\u03bf\u03c5 1912-1913|trans-title=The Victorious Greco-Turkish War of 1912-1913|volume=I|publisher=Estia|location=Athens|language=Greek|year=1913|url=https://anemi.lib.uoc.gr/metadata/8/d/1/metadata-9272bd94229998ed96a378ab0f986a22_1270023610.tkl|accessdate=13 November 2019|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |first1=Georgios|last1=Christopoulos|first2=Ioannis|last2=Bastias|title=\u0399\u03c3\u03c4\u03bf\u03c1\u03af\u03b1 \u03c4\u03bf\u03c5 \u0395\u03bb\u03bb\u03b7\u03bd\u03b9\u03ba\u03bf\u03cd \u0395\u03b8\u03bd\u03bf\u03c5\u03c2: \u039d\u03b5\u03ce\u03c4\u03b5\u03c1\u03bf\u03c2 \u0395\u03bb\u03bb\u03b7\u03bd\u03b9\u03c3\u03bc\u03cc\u03c2 \u03b1\u03c0\u03bf \u03c4\u03bf 1881 \u03c9\u03c2 1913|trans-title=History of the Greek Nation: Modern Greece from 1881 until 1913 |volume=XIV |publisher=Ekdotiki Athinon|language=Greek|location=Athens|year=1977 |isbn=960-213-110-1|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Dimitracopoulos |first=Anastasios |title=The First Balkan War Through the Pages of Review L'Illustration |year=1992 |publisher=Hellenic Committee of Military History|location=Athens |oclc= 37043754| ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Erickson |first=Edward |title=Defeat in Detail: The Ottoman Army in the Balkans, 1912-1913 |year=2003|publisher=Praeger|location=Westport | isbn =978-0-275-97888-4| ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Kargakos |first=Sarandos| title=\u0397 \u0395\u03bb\u03bb\u03ac\u03c2 \u03ba\u03b1\u03c4\u03ac \u03c4\u03bf\u03c5\u03c2 \u0392\u03b1\u03bb\u03ba\u03b1\u03bd\u03b9\u03ba\u03bf\u03cd\u03c2 \u03a0\u03bf\u03bb\u03ad\u03bc\u03bf\u03c5\u03c2 (1912-1913)|trans-title=Greece in the Balkan Wars (1912-1913)| publisher=Peritechnon|location=Athens| year = 2012 | isbn =978-960-8411-26-5|language=Greek| ref=harv}}\n* {{cite web |last=Katsikostas |first=Dimitrios |title=\u0397 \u03b1\u03bd\u03b1\u03b4\u03b9\u03bf\u03c1\u03b3\u03ac\u03bd\u03c9\u03c3\u03b7 \u03c4\u03c9\u03bd \u03b5\u03bd\u03cc\u03c0\u03bb\u03c9\u03bd \u03b4\u03c5\u03bd\u03ac\u03bc\u03b5\u03c9\u03bd \u03ba\u03b1\u03b9 \u03c4\u03bf \u03ad\u03c1\u03b3\u03bf \u03c4\u03b7\u03c2 \u03b3\u03b1\u03bb\u03bb\u03b9\u03ba\u03ae\u03c2 \u03c3\u03c4\u03c1\u03b1\u03c4\u03b9\u03c9\u03c4\u03b9\u03ba\u03ae\u03c2 \u03b1\u03c0\u03bf\u03c3\u03c4\u03bf\u03bb\u03ae\u03c2 Eydoux|trans-title=The Reorganization of the Armed Forces and the Efforts of the French Military Mission of Eydoux|publisher= Hellenic Army History Directorate |language=Greek|year= 2014 |url=https://dis.army.gr/sites/dis.army.gr/files/unmanaged/pdf/Articles_June14/Greek_French/ANADIORG_ED_APOST_EYDOUX.pdf|accessdate=13 November 2019 | ref=harv}}\n{{Refend}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sarantaporo 1912}}\n[[Category:Battles of the First Balkan War]]\n[[Category:Conflicts in 1912]]\n[[Category:Battles involving the Ottoman Empire]]\n[[Category:Battles involving Greece]]\n[[Category:1912 in Greece]]\n[[Category:1912 in the Ottoman Empire]]\n[[Category:Manastir Vilayet]]\n[[Category:Modern history of Thessaly]]\n[[Category:October 1912 events]]\n", "text_old": "{{good article}}\n{{Infobox Military Conflict\n|conflict=Battle of Sarantaporo\n|partof=the [[First Balkan War]]   \n|image=Sarantaporo.png\n|image_size=250px\n|caption=Map of the battle\n|date=9 \u2013 10 October 1912 (O.S.)    \n|place=[[Sarantaporo]], [[Manastir Vilayet]], [[Ottoman Empire]] (present-day [[Greece]])  \n|result= Greek victory \n* Greek army captures [[Servia, Greece|Servia]] and [[Kozani]]\n|map_type    = Greece\n| map_label   =Sarantaporo\n|map_relief  = yes\n|alt         = A relief map of modern day Greece, with the location of the battle marked.\n|map_caption ={{center|Location of the battle in present day Greece}}\n|coordinates={{coord|40.0400|N|22.0300|E|display=title}}\n|combatant1={{flagicon|Greece|royal}} [[Kingdom of Greece|Greece]]  \n|combatant2={{flag|Ottoman Empire}}   \n|commander1=Crown Prince [[Constantine I of Greece|Constantine]]\n|commander2=General [[Hasan Tahsin Pasha]]\n|units1=[[Order of battle of the Hellenic Army in the First Balkan War#Army of Thessaly|Army of Thessaly]]\n*[[1st Infantry Division (Greece)|1st Infantry Division]]\n*[[2nd Infantry Division (Greece)|2nd Infantry Division]]\n*[[3rd Infantry Division (Greece)|3rd Infantry Division]]\n*[[4th Infantry Division (Greece)|4th Infantry Division]]   \n*[[5th Infantry Division (Greece)|5th Infantry Division]]\n|units2=[[VIII Corps (Ottoman Empire)|VIII Provisional Corps]]\n*[[22nd Infantry Division (Ottoman Empire)|22nd Infantry Division]]\n*Nasli\u00e7 Division\n|strength1=''5 divisions''\n|strength2=''2 divisions''\n|casualties1=182 killed<br>1,000 wounded {{sfn|Christopoulos|Bastias|1977|p=292}}\n|casualties2=500 killed<br />1,000 wounded<br />22-25 field artillery pieces {{sfn|Erickson|2003|pp=218\u2013219}}\n}}   \n{{Campaignbox First Balkan War}}\n\nThe '''Battle of Sarantaporo''', also variously transliterated as '''Sarantaporon''' or '''Sarandaporon''' ({{lang-el|\u039c\u03ac\u03c7\u03b7 \u03c4\u03bf\u03c5 \u03a3\u03b1\u03c1\u03b1\u03bd\u03c4\u03b1\u03c0\u03cc\u03c1\u03bf\u03c5}}), took place on October 9 \u2013 10 (O.S.), 1912. It was the first major battle fought between [[Kingdom of Greece|Greek]] and [[Ottoman Empire|Ottoman]] forces during the [[First Balkan War]], and revolved around the Sarandaporo pass, which connected [[Thessaly]] with central [[Macedonia (region)|Macedonia]].\n\nDespite being perceived as impregnable by its defenders, the main body of the Greek forces managed to advance deep inside the pass, while auxiliary units broke through the Ottoman flanks. The Ottomans abandoned their defensive line during the night, fearing encirclement. The Greek victory at Sarandaporo opened the way for the capture of [[Servia, Greece|Servia]] and [[Kozani]].\n\n==Background==\nThe disastrous Greek defeat in the [[Greco-Turkish War (1897)|Greco-Turkish War]] of 1897 exposed major flaws in the [[Greek Army]]'s organization, training and logistics. Upon his appointment in December 1905, [[Georgios Theotokis]] became the first post-war Greek prime minister to focus his attention on strengthening the army. He established the National Defense Fund which financed the purchase of large quantities of ammunition. In addition a new [[table of organization]] was introduced for the country's [[Greek Navy|navy]] and army, the latter being augmented by numerous artillery batteries. Theotokis' resignation in January 1909 and the perceived neglect of the armed forces by his successor resulted in the [[Goudi coup]] seven months later. Rather than taking power for themselves, the putschists invited Cretan politician [[Eleftherios Venizelos]] to rule the country.{{sfn|Kargakos|2012|pp=19\u201321}} Venizelos followed in Theotokis' footsteps by continuing to re-arm and re-train the military, enacted extensive fortification and infrastructure works, purchased new weapons, and recalled the [[Military reserve force|reserve classes]] for training. The climax of this effort was the invitation in 1911 of a [[British naval mission to Greece (1911\u20131915)|British naval mission]] and a [[French military mission to Greece (1911\u20131914)|French military mission]].{{sfn|Katsikostas|2014|pp=5\u20136}} \n\nAfter being informed of a Serbo-Bulgarian alliance, Venizelos ordered his ambassador in [[Sofia]] to prepare a Greco-Bulgarian defense agreement by 14 April 1912. Fearing that should Greece fail to participate in a future war against the [[Ottoman Empire|Ottomans]], it would be unable to capture the Greek majority areas of [[Macedonia (region)|Macedonia]]. The treaty was signed on 15 July 1912, with the two countries agreeing to assist each other in case of a defensive war and to safeguard the rights of Christian populations in Ottoman held Macedonia, thus joining the loose [[Balkan League]] alliance with [[Serbia]], [[Montenegro]] and [[Bulgaria]]. Fearing a new war in the Balkans, the Ottomans mobilized their armed forces on 14 September and began transferring units to [[Thrace]]; the Balkan League responded in kind.{{sfn|Kargakos|2012|pp=26\u201329}} On 30 September, the League presented the Ottomans with a list of demands regarding the rights of its Christian population. The Ottoman Empire rebuffed the demands, recalled its ambassadors in Sofia, Belgrade and Athens and expelled the League's negotiators on 4 October. The League's negotiators declared [[First Balkan War|war]] against the Ottomans, while Montenegro had already began military operations on 25 September.{{sfn|Kargakos|2012|pp=35\u201338}}\n\n==Prelude==\nGreece dispatched the [[Army of Epirus]] and the [[Army of Thessaly]] to its frontiers in [[Epirus]] and [[Thessaly]] respectively. The latter numbered 100,000 men, and was divided into seven divisions: namely the [[1st Infantry Division (Greece)|1st Infantry Division]], the [[2nd Infantry Division (Greece)|2nd Infantry Division]], the [[3rd Infantry Division (Greece)|3rd Infantry Division]], the [[4th Infantry Division (Greece)|4th Infantry Division]], the [[5th Infantry Division (Greece)|5th Infantry Division]], the [[6th Infantry Division (Greece)|6th Infantry Division]] and the [[7th Mechanized Infantry Brigade (Greece)|7th Infantry Division]], as well as a cavalry brigade and four independent [[Evzones]] battalions. The Army of Thessaly was commanded by Crown Prince [[Constantine I of Greece|Constantine]].{{sfn|Christopoulos|Bastias|1977|pp=289\u2013290}} Facing the Greeks in Thessaly was the Ottoman [[VIII Corps (Ottoman Empire)|VIII Corps]] under General [[Hasan Tahsin Pasha]] which included three divisions: the regular (''nizamiye'') [[22nd Infantry Division (Ottoman Empire)|22nd Division]] and the reserve (''redif'') Nasli\u00e7 and Ayd\u0131n Divisions{{sfn|Erickson|2003|p=170}} which, combined with the Ottoman garrisons in western Macedonia, totaled 35,000-40,000 men.{{sfn|Christopoulos|Bastias|1977|p=290}}\n\nThe Army of Thessaly crossed into Ottoman territory in the early morning hours of 5 October, finding most border posts to be abandoned, with the garrisons at Melouna Pass, Profitis Ilias and Tsouka resisting for several hours before retreating. The first major clashes took place the following day when the 1st and 2nd Greek Divisions attacked hastily organized defenses north of [[Elassona]]. Elassona was defended by three infantry battalions, two artillery batteries and half a squadron of cavalry.{{sfn|Christopoulos|Bastias|1977|p=290}} The battle for Elassona lasted for three hours, with the Ottomans retreating to avoid encirclement, thus giving the troops manning the main defensive line at Sarandaporo additional time to reinforce their positions.{{sfn|Kargakos|2012|pp=44\u201345}} The Greeks went on to advance {{convert|20|km|miles}} into the Elassona plateau without encountering any resistance.{{sfn|Kargakos|2012|p=47}} Between 7 and 8 October, Greek troops regrouped in front of Sarandaporo and dispatched cavalry reconnaissance patrols towards the Ottoman positions, locating the headquarters of the Ottoman VIII Provisional Corps at Hania Viglas and those of a reserve division at Glikovo.{{sfn|Christopoulos|Bastias|1977|p=290}}\n\nSituated between the Vigla and Amorves mountains, Sarandaporo was a narrow mountain pass, the only one connecting Thessaly with central Macedonia; it spanned some {{convert|7-8|km|miles|sigfig=1}}. Having ceded Thessaly to Greece in the [[Convention of Constantinople (1881)]], the Ottomans began methodically reinforcing their positions around Sarandaporo in anticipation of a future war.{{sfn|Kargakos|2012|p=48}} The Ottomans had organized their defenses under the guidance of German military advisors, placing their artillery batteries and infantry in sheltered, camouflaged trenches on the ravine's steep slopes, allowing them to accurately fire along its entire length. Considered to be nearly impenetrable it was dubbed \"the graveyard of the Greek Army\" by  the Prussian Field Marshal [[Colmar Freiherr von der Goltz]].{{sfn|Dimitracopoulos|1992|p=42}}\n\n==Battle==\nAt 7 a.m. on 9 October, the Greek infantry began its assault on Sarandaporo. The 1st, 2nd and 3rd Divisions attacked the Ottoman main line frontally, their advance hampered by accurate Ottoman rifle and artillery fire and the ruggedness of the terrain. In the meantime, the 4th Division conducted a flanking maneuver from the west with the intention of occupying the Porta Pass, and striking the rear of the Ottoman positions.{{sfn|Christopoulos|Bastias|1977|p=291}} The 5th Division advanced further to the west towards the village of Zampourda which was situated on the other bank of the [[Haliacmon]], with the intention of protecting the left flank of the Greek forces emerging from the Sarandaporo pass. The cavalry brigade moved on the extreme west along the road towards [[Servia, Greece|Servia]], planning to block the bridge across the Haliacmon.{{sfn|Kargakos|2012|p=51}} Attacking from the east of the pass the Konstantinopoulos Evzone detachment overcame stiff resistance at Vlacholeivado and captured the village, but failing to advance further due to heavy fog.{{sfn|Apostolidis|1913|pp=207\u2013209}}{{sfn|Christopoulos|Bastias|1977|p=291}} At 2 p.m., the main bulk of the Greek artillery was brought to the main line, joining the engagement. Despite suffering heavy casualties, the three divisions had halted some {{convert|500-700|m|miles}} from the Ottoman trenches intending to launch a final assault the following morning.{{sfn|Christopoulos|Bastias|1977|p=291}}\n\nThe 4th Division fought its way through the Metaxas and Rachovo villages. Upon reaching the Porta Pass it engaged in a sanguine clash with the defenders, securing its objective at 5 p.m.{{sfn|Kargakos|2012|p=53}} The 5th Division and the Gennadis Evzone detachment were confronted by four Ottoman reserve battalions at Lazarades which held their ground until sunset.{{sfn|Christopoulos|Bastias|1977|p=291}} The commander of the cavalry brigade ordered his unit to encamp at Loudani, refusing to advance further because of the resistance offered by the Ottomans at Lazarades. Fearing that they would be encircled by the Konstantinopoulos Evzone detachment, the Ottomans began to withdraw at 7 p.m., towards their second defensive line at Hani 739, under the cover of the night. Before retreating they fired a 20-minute artillery barrage on Greek positions along the entire frontline. Unaware of the Ottoman retreat the Greeks failed to use the opportunity and cut their access to the bridge across the Haliacmon. Upon reaching their second defensive line, the Ottomans became aware of the 4th Divisions' seizure of Porta Pass, panic spread in their ranks and many soldiers began fleeing and abandoning their equipment.{{sfn|Apostolidis|1913|pp=203\u2013205}} On the morning of 10 October, the 4th Division charged down the northern slope of the Rahovo Mountain, surprising the Ottoman infantry and artillerymen who abandoned over twenty [[Krupp gun]]s and engaged in a disorganized retreat.{{sfn|Dimitracopoulos|1992|p=44}}{{sfn|Erickson|2003|pp=218\u2013219}} The Greek cavalry's indecision once again enabled the fleeing Ottomans to safely reach Servia and [[Kozani]].{{sfn|Kargakos|2012|pp=56\u201357}}\n\n==Aftermath==\nAt 4 p.m. on 10 October, the 4th Division entered Servia, witnessing 75 to 90 severed human heads lined up on either side of one of its streets.{{sfn|Dimitracopoulos|1992|p=44}}{{sfn|Christopoulos|Bastias|1977|p=292}} Following the declaration of war local authorities had detained all the Christian dignitaries from Servia and the surrounding villages with the intention of massacring them, a plan that was thwarted by Ottoman officer Omer Bey. However, upon realizing the imminent defeat of the Ottoman troops at Sarandaporo, the town's Muslim population massacred 117 local Christians.{{sfn|Kargakos|2012|pp=58\u201359}} By 11 October, the entirety of the Army of Thessaly had reached the banks of the Haliacmon, while the Greek cavalry entered Kozani unopposed,{{sfn|Christopoulos|Bastias|1977|p=292}} opening the way for the Greeks to advance towards the Greek majority city of [[Thessaloniki]] and assist the Serbs at [[Bitola|Monastir]].{{sfn|Dimitracopoulos|1992|p=46}} On 13 October, the Greek army transferred its general headquarters to Kozani; the following day King [[George I of Greece|George I]] arrived in the city, ordering the army to march towards Thessaloniki and [[Veroia]].{{sfn|Apostolidis|1913|pp=241\u2013243}} Greek casualties in the battle of Sarandaporo numbered 182 killed and over 1,000 wounded,{{sfn|Christopoulos|Bastias|1977|p=292}} while the Ottomans lost 500 killed, 1,000 wounded, around 22 to 25 field artillery pieces captured and other significant material losses.{{sfn|Erickson|2003|pp=218\u2013219}}{{sfn|Dimitracopoulos|1992|p=44}}\n\nBy May 1913, the numerically inferior Ottomans had suffered a series of serious defeats to the League's armies on all fronts. The League had captured most of the Ottoman Empire's European territories and was rapidly approaching [[Constantinople]]. On 30 May, the two sides signed the [[Treaty of London (1913)|Treaty of London]] which solidified the League's territorial ambitions, granting its members all Ottoman lands west of [[Enos, Turkey|Enos]] on the [[Aegean Sea]] and north of [[K\u0131y\u0131k\u00f6y|Midia]] on the [[Black Sea]], as well as [[Crete]]. The fate of [[Albania]] and the Ottoman-held Aegean islands was to be determined by the [[International relations of the Great Powers (1814\u20131919)|Great Powers]].{{sfn|Christopoulos|Bastias|1977|pp=330\u2013332}}\n\n==Footnotes==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==References==\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite book |last=Apostolidis |first=Dimitrios |title=\u039f \u03bd\u03b9\u03ba\u03b7\u03c6\u03cc\u03c1\u03bf\u03c2 \u03b5\u03bb\u03bb\u03b7\u03bd\u03bf\u03c4\u03bf\u03c5\u03c1\u03ba\u03b9\u03ba\u03cc\u03c2 \u03c0\u03cc\u03bb\u03b5\u03bc\u03bf\u03c2 \u03c4\u03bf\u03c5 1912-1913|trans-title=The Victorious Greco-Turkish War of 1912-1913|volume=I|publisher=Estia|location=Athens|language=Greek|year=1913|url=https://anemi.lib.uoc.gr/metadata/8/d/1/metadata-9272bd94229998ed96a378ab0f986a22_1270023610.tkl|accessdate=13 November 2019|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |first1=Georgios|last1=Christopoulos|first2=Ioannis|last2=Bastias|title=\u0399\u03c3\u03c4\u03bf\u03c1\u03af\u03b1 \u03c4\u03bf\u03c5 \u0395\u03bb\u03bb\u03b7\u03bd\u03b9\u03ba\u03bf\u03cd \u0395\u03b8\u03bd\u03bf\u03c5\u03c2: \u039d\u03b5\u03ce\u03c4\u03b5\u03c1\u03bf\u03c2 \u0395\u03bb\u03bb\u03b7\u03bd\u03b9\u03c3\u03bc\u03cc\u03c2 \u03b1\u03c0\u03bf \u03c4\u03bf 1881 \u03c9\u03c2 1913|trans-title=History of the Greek Nation: Modern Greece from 1881 until 1913 |volume=XIV |publisher=Ekdotiki Athinon|language=Greek|location=Athens|year=1977 |isbn=960-213-110-1|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Dimitracopoulos |first=Anastasios |title=The First Balkan War Through the Pages of Review L'Illustration |year=1992 |publisher=Hellenic Committee of Military History|location=Athens |oclc= 37043754| ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Erickson |first=Edward |title=Defeat in Detail: The Ottoman Army in the Balkans, 1912-1913 |year=2003|publisher=Praeger|location=Westport | isbn =978-0-275-97888-4| ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book |last=Kargakos |first=Sarandos| title=\u0397 \u0395\u03bb\u03bb\u03ac\u03c2 \u03ba\u03b1\u03c4\u03ac \u03c4\u03bf\u03c5\u03c2 \u0392\u03b1\u03bb\u03ba\u03b1\u03bd\u03b9\u03ba\u03bf\u03cd\u03c2 \u03a0\u03bf\u03bb\u03ad\u03bc\u03bf\u03c5\u03c2 (1912-1913)|trans-title=Greece in the Balkan Wars (1912-1913)| publisher=Peritechnon|location=Athens| year = 2012 | isbn =978-960-8411-26-5|language=Greek| ref=harv}}\n* {{cite web |last=Katsikostas |first=Dimitrios |title=\u0397 \u03b1\u03bd\u03b1\u03b4\u03b9\u03bf\u03c1\u03b3\u03ac\u03bd\u03c9\u03c3\u03b7 \u03c4\u03c9\u03bd \u03b5\u03bd\u03cc\u03c0\u03bb\u03c9\u03bd \u03b4\u03c5\u03bd\u03ac\u03bc\u03b5\u03c9\u03bd \u03ba\u03b1\u03b9 \u03c4\u03bf \u03ad\u03c1\u03b3\u03bf \u03c4\u03b7\u03c2 \u03b3\u03b1\u03bb\u03bb\u03b9\u03ba\u03ae\u03c2 \u03c3\u03c4\u03c1\u03b1\u03c4\u03b9\u03c9\u03c4\u03b9\u03ba\u03ae\u03c2 \u03b1\u03c0\u03bf\u03c3\u03c4\u03bf\u03bb\u03ae\u03c2 Eydoux|trans-title=The Reorganization of the Armed Forces and the Efforts of the French Military Mission of Eydoux|publisher= Hellenic Army History Directorate |language=Greek|year= 2014 |url=https://dis.army.gr/sites/dis.army.gr/files/unmanaged/pdf/Articles_June14/Greek_French/ANADIORG_ED_APOST_EYDOUX.pdf|accessdate=13 November 2019 | ref=harv}}\n{{Refend}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sarantaporo 1912}}\n[[Category:Battles of the First Balkan War]]\n[[Category:Conflicts in 1912]]\n[[Category:Battles involving the Ottoman Empire]]\n[[Category:Battles involving Greece]]\n[[Category:1912 in Greece]]\n[[Category:1912 in the Ottoman Empire]]\n[[Category:Manastir Vilayet]]\n[[Category:Modern history of Thessaly]]\n[[Category:October 1912 events]]\n", "name_user": "Catlemur", "label": "safe", "comment": "ce", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Battle_of_Sarantaporo"}
{"title_page": "Spy vs. Spy (1984 video game)", "text_new": "{{about|the 1984 computer game|2005 Playstation 2 game|Spy vs. Spy (2005 video game)}}\n{{Infobox video game\n| title          = Spy vs. Spy\n| image          = Spy vs Spy cover.jpg\n| caption        = European Commodore 64 cover art\n| developer      = [[First Star Software]]\n| publisher      = [[Beyond Software]] (UK)<br>[[Tynesoft]] (BBC, Electron)<br>Wicked Software (Amiga, ST)<br>[[Kemco]] (NES, GBC)<br>Robots and Pencils (iOS)\n| composer       = Nick Scarim<br>Hiroyuki Masuno\n| designer       = Michael Riedel <ref name=giantlist/>\n| programmer     = '''Commodore 64'''<br>Michael Riedel <ref name=giantlist/><br>'''Atari 8-bit'''<br>Jim Nangano<ref name=giantlist/>\n| series         = \n| released       = {{collapsible list|title=1984|\n'''Atari 8-bit'''<br>{{Video game release|NA|1984}}'''Commodore 64'''<br>{{Video game release|NA|1984}}'''Amstrad CPC'''<br>{{Video game release|NA|1985}}'''Apple II'''<br>{{Video game release|NA|1985}}'''ZX Spectrum'''<br>{{Video game release|NA|1985}}'''NES'''<br>{{Video game release|JP|April 26, 1986|NA|September01 - October 31, 1988<ref>http://www.gamingrebellion.com/2014/12/spy-vs-spy-nes-release/</ref>|PAL|July 27, 1990}}'''Master System'''<ref>http://uk.gamespot.com/sms/action/spyvsspy/similar.html?mode=versions{{dead link|date=March 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><br>{{Video game release|JP|September 20, 1986|NA|1986|PAL|1986}}'''Amiga'''<br>{{Video game release|NA|1989}}'''Atari ST'''<br>{{Video game release|NA|1989}}'''Game Boy'''<br>{{Video game release|NA|January 16, 1991}}'''Game Boy Color'''<br>{{Video game release|NA|August 1, 1999}}\n}}\n| genre          = \n| modes          = [[single-player video game|Single-player]], [[multiplayer]]\n| platforms      = [[Acorn Electron]], [[Amiga]], [[Amstrad CPC]], [[Apple II]], [[Atari 8-bit]], [[Atari ST]], [[BBC Micro]], [[Commodore 64]] [[Commodore 16 |/ 16]], [[Game Boy]], [[Game Boy Color]], [[MSX]], [[NES]], [[Master System]], [[Sharp X1]], [[ZX Spectrum]]\n}}\n\n'''''Spy vs. Spy''''' is a video game written by Michael Riedel for the [[Commodore 64]] and published by [[First Star Software]] in 1984. A port for the [[Atari 8-bit family]] was released simultaneously. It is a two-player, split-screen game, based on ''[[Mad (magazine)|Mad]]'' magazine's long-running cartoon strip ''[[Spy vs. Spy]]'', about the slapstick antics of two spies trying to kill each other with improbably elaborate traps and weapons.\n\nIt was ported to the [[Apple II]], [[ZX Spectrum]], [[Acorn Electron]], [[Atari ST]], [[BBC Micro]], [[Commodore 16]], [[MSX]], [[Amstrad CPC]], [[Amiga]], [[Master System]], [[Game Boy family|Game Boy]], [[Game Boy Color]], and [[Nintendo Entertainment System]], which was emulated on the [[Game Boy Advance]].\n\n==Gameplay==\n[[Image:Spy vs Spy A800 ingame.png|left|thumb|White Spy has just found the briefcase (Atari 8-bit)]]\nThe object of the game is to collect various secret items in a briefcase and exit the building through a door to the airport, either before the opposing player exits or before the timer runs out.  While searching for the items, traps can be laid to take out the opponent (or the player himself, if careless). Each spy has a personal countdown timer which depletes by 30 seconds upon each death.\n\nThe arena is an [[embassy]], constructed from a series of interconnected rooms laid out on a grid pattern. Higher levels have more rooms and therefore a larger play area. The spies can engage in hand-to-hand combat (achieved by wiggling the [[joystick]] or [[directional pad]] left and right or up and down when the spies are in proximity to each other) as well as place traps on the furniture and doors which occupy the playing area. These traps are triggered when a spy searches a piece of furniture or opens a booby trapped door, resulting in a cartoon-style animation showing the subject being shot, blown up, etc., and floating up to heaven as an angel.\n\nStrategy is introduced by limiting the numbers of each trap a spy can use and by allowing the traps to be triggered by either spy. Some pieces of furniture also contain 'remedies' which match up to specific traps; these allow a trap to be defused, but can only be fetched one at a time.\n\n==Reception==\n''[[Video (magazine)|Video]]'' magazine described it as \"a rousing action-strategy contest\" and praised the game's \"excellent\" graphics as \"befit[ting] a game so rooted in a visual medium.\" The reviewer also noted that \"no one has more successfully captured the original feel of the source nor offered a more satisfying result\".<ref>{{cite magazine |last= Kunkel |first= Bill |author-link= Bill Kunkel (gaming)|date= February 1985 |title= Random Access: Spy vs. Spy |magazine=Video|publisher= Reese Communications|volume= 8|issue= 11|page= 35|issn= 0147-8907}}</ref> ''[[Ahoy!]]'' agreed in its review, calling it a faithful adaptation of the comics and praising both the simultaneous two-player and one-player options.<ref name=\"fried198503\">{{cite news | url=https://archive.org/stream/Ahoy_Issue_15_1985-03_Ion_International_US#page/n31/mode/2upp | title=Spy vs. Spy | work=Ahoy! | date=March 1985 | accessdate=27 June 2014 | author=Fried, Greg | pages=33\u201334}}</ref> ''[[Antic (magazine)|Antic]]'' called it \"one of the most original and clever games for the Atari computers yet\". The magazine praised the simultaneous two-player display and concluded, \"I cannot recommend this game highly enough.\"<ref name=\"bernstein198505\">{{cite news | url=https://archive.org/stream/1985-05-anticmagazine/Antic_Vol_4-01_1985-05_New_Super_Ataris#page/n79/mode/2up | title=Spy vs. Spy | work=Antic | date=May 1985 | accessdate=8 January 2015 | author=Bernstein, Harvey |page=81}}</ref> The ZX Spectrum version was rated number 20 in the ''[[Your Sinclair]] Official Top 100 Games of All Time''.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Readers' Top 100 Games of All Time|journal=Your Sinclair|date=September 1993}}</ref>\n\n== Legacy==\n[[Image:Spy vs Spy II A800 ingame.png|right|thumb|''Spy vs. Spy II''. When in the same room, both players use the same screen, leaving the other blank.]]\n[[Image:Spy vs Spy III A800 ingame.png|right|thumb|''Spy vs. Spy III'']]\n\nA remake including the original version was released for iOS in 2012, but is no longer available.\n\nTwo sequels to the original 1984 game were produced: ''Spy vs. Spy II: The Island Caper'' and ''Spy vs. Spy III: Arctic Antics''. The third game was also released for the [[IBM PC]]. These kept the basic gameplay while tweaking some core features.<ref name=\"farrell\">{{cite journal|last=Farrell|first=Andrew|title=''Spy vs Spy II'' Review|journal=The Australian Commodore Review|volume=2|issue=7|page=6|publisher=Saturday Magazine Pty|issn=0816-5874|oclc=217544012}}</ref>\n\n{{anchor|islandcaper}}'''''Spy vs. Spy II: The Island Caper'''''<ref name='atarimania2'>http://www.atarimania.com/game-atari-400-800-xl-xe-spy-vs-spy-ii_6757.html</ref> adds a side-scrolling play area.<ref name=\"farrell\"/> Spies no longer start with a fixed number of traps but must collect the raw materials to build them\n\n{{anchor|arcticantics}}'''''Spy vs. Spy III: Arctic Antics'''''<ref name='atarimania3'>http://www.atarimania.com/game-atari-400-800-xl-xe-spy-vs-spy-iii_6197.html</ref> switches the location from a tropical island to the [[arctic]]. The spies fight by throwing snowballs at each other and setting traps, which decreases their body heat bar. Tools include a saw to cut holes in the ice for the second player to fall into. Lost body heat can be restored by moving into a heated igloo.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|refs=\n<ref name=\"giantlist\">{{cite web |last1=Hague |first1=James |title=The Giant List of Classic Game Programmers |url=https://dadgum.com/giantlist/}}</ref>\n}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{WoS game|id=0004786|name=Spy vs. Spy}}\n*{{lemon64 game|id=2438|name=Spy vs. Spy}}\n*[http://www.atarimania.com/game-atari-400-800-xl-xe-spy-vs-spy_4956.html ''Spy vs. Spy''] at Atari Mania\n*[https://archive.org/details/C64Gamevideoarchive105-SpyVsSpy/ Video from the C64 version] on archive.org\n\n[[Category:1984 video games]]\n[[Category:Amiga games]]\n[[Category:Amstrad CPC games]]\n[[Category:Apple II games]]\n[[Category:Atari 8-bit family games]]\n[[Category:Atari ST games]]\n[[Category:BBC Micro and Acorn Electron games]]\n[[Category:Commodore 64 games]]\n[[Category:Commodore 16 and Plus/4 games]]\n[[Category:Game Boy games]]\n[[Category:Game Boy Color games]]\n[[Category:IOS games]]\n[[Category:MSX games]]\n[[Category:NEC PC-8801 games]]\n[[Category:Nintendo Entertainment System games]]\n[[Category:PlayStation 2 games]]\n[[Category:Master System games]]\n[[Category:Sharp X1 games]]\n[[Category:Video games based on Spy vs. Spy]]\n[[Category:ZX Spectrum games]]\n[[Category:Split-screen multiplayer games]]\n[[Category:Video games developed in the United States]]\n\n[[fr:Spy vs. Spy]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|the 1984 computer game|2005 Playstation 2 game|Spy vs. Spy (2005 video game)}}\n{{Infobox video game\n| title          = Spy vs. Spy\n| image          = Spy vs Spy cover.jpg\n| caption        = European Commodore 64 cover art\n| developer      = [[First Star Software]]\n| publisher      = [[Beyond Software]] (UK)<br>[[Tynesoft]] (BBC, Electron)<br>Wicked Software (Amiga, ST)<br>[[Kemco]] (NES, GBC)<br>Robots and Pencils (iOS)\n| composer       = Nick Scarim<br>Hiroyuki Masuno\n| designer       = Michael Riedel <ref name=giantlist/>\n| programmer     = '''Commodore 64'''<br>Michael Riedel <ref name=giantlist/><br>'''Atari 8-bit'''<br>Jim Nangano<ref name=giantlist/>\n| series         = \n| released       = {{collapsible list|title=1984|\n'''Atari 8-bit'''<br>{{Video game release|NA|1984}}'''Commodore 64'''<br>{{Video game release|NA|1984}}'''Amstrad CPC'''<br>{{Video game release|NA|1985}}'''Apple II'''<br>{{Video game release|NA|1985}}'''ZX Spectrum'''<br>{{Video game release|NA|1985}}'''NES'''<br>{{Video game release|JP|April 26, 1986|NA|September01 - October 31, 1988<ref>http://www.gamingrebellion.com/2014/12/spy-vs-spy-nes-release/</ref>|PAL|July 27, 1990}}'''Master System'''<ref>http://uk.gamespot.com/sms/action/spyvsspy/similar.html?mode=versions{{dead link|date=March 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><br>{{Video game release|JP|September 20, 1986|NA|1986|PAL|1986}}'''Amiga'''<br>{{Video game release|NA|1989}}'''Atari ST'''<br>{{Video game release|NA|1989}}'''Game Boy'''<br>{{Video game release|NA|January 16, 1991}}'''Game Boy Color'''<br>{{Video game release|NA|August 1, 1999}}\n}}\n| genre          = \n| modes          = [[single-player video game|Single-player]], [[multiplayer]]\n| platforms      = [[Acorn Electron]], [[Amiga]], [[Amstrad CPC]], [[Apple II]], [[Atari 8-bit]], [[Atari ST]], [[BBC Micro]], [[Commodore 64]] [[Commodore 16 |/ 16]], [[Game Boy]], [[Game Boy Color]], [[MSX]], [[NES]], [[Master System]], [[Sharp X1]], [[ZX Spectrum]]\n}}\n\n'''''Spy vs. Spy''''' is a video game written by Michael Riedel for the [[Commodore 64]] and published by [[First Star Software]] in 1984. A port for the [[Atari 8-bit family]] was released simultaneously. It is a two-player, split-screen game, based on ''[[Mad (magazine)|Mad]]'' magazine's long-running cartoon strip ''[[Spy vs. Spy]]'', about the slapstick antics of two spies trying to kill each other with improbably elaborate traps and weapons.\n\nIt was ported to the [[Apple II]], [[ZX Spectrum]], [[Acorn Electron]], [[Atari ST]], [[BBC Micro]], [[Commodore 16]], [[MSX]], [[Amstrad CPC]], [[Amiga]], [[Master System]], [[Game Boy family|Game Boy]], [[Game Boy Color]], and [[Nintendo Entertainment System]], which was emulated on the [[Game Boy Advance]].\n\n==Gameplay==\n[[Image:Spy vs Spy A800 ingame.png|left|thumb|White Spy has just found the briefcase (Atari 8-bit)]]\nThe object of the game is to collect various secret items in a briefcase and exit the building through a door to the airport, either before the opposing player exits or before the timer runs out.  While searching for the items, traps can be laid to take out the opponent (or the player himself, if careless). Each spy has a personal countdown timer which depletes by 30 seconds upon each death.\n\nThe arena is an [[embassy]], constructed from a series of interconnected rooms laid out on a grid pattern. Higher levels have more rooms and therefore a larger play area. The spies can engage in hand-to-hand combat (achieved by wiggling the [[joystick]] or [[directional pad]] left and right or up and down when the spies are in proximity to each other) as well as place traps on the furniture and doors which occupy the playing area. These traps are triggered when a spy searches a piece of furniture or opens a booby trapped door, resulting in a cartoon-style animation showing the subject being shot, blown up, etc, and floating up to heaven as an angel.\n\nStrategy is introduced by limiting the numbers of each trap a spy can use and by allowing the traps to be triggered by either spy. Some pieces of furniture also contain 'remedies' which match up to specific traps; these allow a trap to be defused, but can only be fetched one at a time.\n\n==Reception==\n''[[Video (magazine)|Video]]'' magazine described it as \"a rousing action-strategy contest\" and praised the game's \"excellent\" graphics as \"befit[ting] a game so rooted in a visual medium.\" The reviewer also noted that \"no one has more successfully captured the original feel of the source nor offered a more satisfying result\".<ref>{{cite magazine |last= Kunkel |first= Bill |author-link= Bill Kunkel (gaming)|date= February 1985 |title= Random Access: Spy vs. Spy |magazine=Video|publisher= Reese Communications|volume= 8|issue= 11|page= 35|issn= 0147-8907}}</ref> ''[[Ahoy!]]'' agreed in its review, calling it a faithful adaptation of the comics and praising both the simultaneous two-player and one-player options.<ref name=\"fried198503\">{{cite news | url=https://archive.org/stream/Ahoy_Issue_15_1985-03_Ion_International_US#page/n31/mode/2upp | title=Spy vs. Spy | work=Ahoy! | date=March 1985 | accessdate=27 June 2014 | author=Fried, Greg | pages=33\u201334}}</ref> ''[[Antic (magazine)|Antic]]'' called it \"one of the most original and clever games for the Atari computers yet\". The magazine praised the simultaneous two-player display and concluded, \"I cannot recommend this game highly enough.\"<ref name=\"bernstein198505\">{{cite news | url=https://archive.org/stream/1985-05-anticmagazine/Antic_Vol_4-01_1985-05_New_Super_Ataris#page/n79/mode/2up | title=Spy vs. Spy | work=Antic | date=May 1985 | accessdate=8 January 2015 | author=Bernstein, Harvey |page=81}}</ref> The ZX Spectrum version was rated number 20 in the ''[[Your Sinclair]] Official Top 100 Games of All Time''.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Readers' Top 100 Games of All Time|journal=Your Sinclair|date=September 1993}}</ref>\n\n== Legacy==\n[[Image:Spy vs Spy II A800 ingame.png|right|thumb|''Spy vs. Spy II''. When in the same room, both players use the same screen, leaving the other blank.]]\n[[Image:Spy vs Spy III A800 ingame.png|right|thumb|''Spy vs. Spy III'']]\n\nA remake including the original version was released for iOS in 2012, but is no longer available.\n\nTwo sequels to the original 1984 game were produced: ''Spy vs. Spy II: The Island Caper'' and ''Spy vs. Spy III: Arctic Antics''. The third game was also released for the [[IBM PC]]. These kept the basic gameplay while tweaking some core features.<ref name=\"farrell\">{{cite journal|last=Farrell|first=Andrew|title=''Spy vs Spy II'' Review|journal=The Australian Commodore Review|volume=2|issue=7|page=6|publisher=Saturday Magazine Pty|issn=0816-5874|oclc=217544012}}</ref>\n\n{{anchor|islandcaper}}'''''Spy vs. Spy II: The Island Caper'''''<ref name='atarimania2'>http://www.atarimania.com/game-atari-400-800-xl-xe-spy-vs-spy-ii_6757.html</ref> adds a side-scrolling play area.<ref name=\"farrell\"/> Spies no longer start with a fixed number of traps but must collect the raw materials to build them\n\n{{anchor|arcticantics}}'''''Spy vs. Spy III: Arctic Antics'''''<ref name='atarimania3'>http://www.atarimania.com/game-atari-400-800-xl-xe-spy-vs-spy-iii_6197.html</ref> switches the location from a tropical island to the [[arctic]]. The spies fight by throwing snowballs at each other and setting traps, which decreases their body heat bar. Tools include a saw to cut holes in the ice for the second player to fall into. Lost body heat can be restored by moving into a heated igloo.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|refs=\n<ref name=\"giantlist\">{{cite web |last1=Hague |first1=James |title=The Giant List of Classic Game Programmers |url=https://dadgum.com/giantlist/}}</ref>\n}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{WoS game|id=0004786|name=Spy vs. Spy}}\n*{{lemon64 game|id=2438|name=Spy vs. Spy}}\n*[http://www.atarimania.com/game-atari-400-800-xl-xe-spy-vs-spy_4956.html ''Spy vs. Spy''] at Atari Mania\n*[https://archive.org/details/C64Gamevideoarchive105-SpyVsSpy/ Video from the C64 version] on archive.org\n\n[[Category:1984 video games]]\n[[Category:Amiga games]]\n[[Category:Amstrad CPC games]]\n[[Category:Apple II games]]\n[[Category:Atari 8-bit family games]]\n[[Category:Atari ST games]]\n[[Category:BBC Micro and Acorn Electron games]]\n[[Category:Commodore 64 games]]\n[[Category:Commodore 16 and Plus/4 games]]\n[[Category:Game Boy games]]\n[[Category:Game Boy Color games]]\n[[Category:IOS games]]\n[[Category:MSX games]]\n[[Category:NEC PC-8801 games]]\n[[Category:Nintendo Entertainment System games]]\n[[Category:PlayStation 2 games]]\n[[Category:Master System games]]\n[[Category:Sharp X1 games]]\n[[Category:Video games based on Spy vs. Spy]]\n[[Category:ZX Spectrum games]]\n[[Category:Split-screen multiplayer games]]\n[[Category:Video games developed in the United States]]\n\n[[fr:Spy vs. Spy]]\n", "name_user": 